HEADWORD: Shake
<hw>Shake</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>obs. p. p.</pos> of
<er>Shake</er>.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shake
<hw>Shake</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Shook</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shaken</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, (<conjf>Shook</conjf>,
<mark>obs.</mark>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shaken</ets>,
<ets>schaken</ets>, AS. <ets>scacan</ets>, <ets>sceacan</ets>; akin to
Icel. & Sw. <ets>skaka</ets>, OS. <ets>skakan</ets>, to depart, to flee.
⟦root⟧161. Cf. <er>Shock</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
cause to move with quick or violent vibrations; to move rapidly one way
and the other; to make to tremble or shiver; to agitate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As a fig tree casteth her untimely figs, when she is
<qex>shaken</qex> of a mighty wind.</q> <rj><qau>Rev. vi.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ascend my chariot; guide the rapid wheels⟦br⟧
That <qex>shake</qex> heaven's basis.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To move from firmness; to weaken the stability
of; to cause to waver; to impair the resolution of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When his doctrines grew too strong to be <qex>shook</qex> by his
enemies, they persecuted his reputation.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy equal fear that my firm faith and love⟦br⟧
Can by his fraud be <qex>shaken</qex> or seduced.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To give a tremulous tone to; to
trill; <as>as, to <ex>shake</ex> a note in music</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move or remove by agitating; to throw off by a
jolting or vibrating motion; to rid one's self of; -- generally with an
adverb, as <xex>off</xex>, <xex>out</xex>, etc.; <as>as, to
<ex>shake</ex> fruit down from a tree</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shake</qex> off the golden slumber of repose.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'Tis our fast intent⟦br⟧
To <qex>shake</qex> all cares and business from our age.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could scarcely <qex>shake</qex> him out of my company.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To shake a cask</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
knock a cask to pieces and pack the staves.</cd> -- <col><b>To shake
hands</b></col>, <cd>to perform the customary act of civility by
clasping and moving hands, as an expression of greeting, farewell, good
will, agreement, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To shake out a reef</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to untile the reef points and spread more
canvas.</cd> -- <col><b>To shake the bells</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Bell</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To shake the sails</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to luff up in the wind, causing the sails to
shiver.</cd> <au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shake
<hw>Shake</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be agitated with a waving or
vibratory motion; to tremble; to shiver; to quake; to totter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Under his burning wheels⟦br⟧
The steadfast empyrean <qex>shook</qex> throughout,⟦br⟧
All but the throne itself of God.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What danger? Who 's that that <qex>shakes</qex> behind there?</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shaking piece</b></col>, <cd>a name given by butchers to
the piece of beef cut from the under side of the neck.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shake
<hw>Shake</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or
result of shaking; a vacillating or wavering motion; a rapid motion one
way and other; a trembling, quaking, or shivering; agitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great soldier's honor was composed⟦br⟧
Of thicker stuff, which could endure a <qex>shake</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our salutations were very hearty on both sides, consisting of many
kind <qex>shakes</qex> of the hand.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fissure or crack in timber, caused by its being
dried too suddenly.</def> <rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fissure in rock or earth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A rapid alternation of a principal
tone with another represented on the next degree of the staff above or
below it; a trill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the staves of a hogshead
or barrel taken apart.</def> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A shook of staves and headings.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The redshank; -- so called from
the nodding of its head while on the ground.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>No great shakes</b></col>, <cd>of no great
importance.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <au>Byron.</au> -- <col><b>The
shakes</b></col>, <cd>the fever and ague.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.
U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shakedown</ent>⟦br⟧
